The Telegraph - Calcutta (Kolkata) | Business | Business Briefs
                                                                                                               Business Briefs
                              
	 London, Sept.4: World finance leaders focused on banking reforms on Friday as evidence mounted that the worst global recession in decades was finally drawing to a close. US treasury secretary Timothy Geithner called for tougher bank capital requirements to curb risky lending practices, a position supported by Britain. Meanwhile, India will lend up to $10 billion to the International Monetary Fund to make funds available to countries in need. The IMF has forecast that the global economy would shrink 1.3 per cent in 2009, less than its April forecast of a 1.4 per cent, and grow 2.9 per cent in 2010, up from 2.5 per cent predicted earlier.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 4: The petroleum ministry has proposed a 44 per cent hike in the price of natural gas produced by ONGC and Oil India and indexing it to inflation to help them cut losses on selling fuel below cost.                             
	 New Delhi, Sept. 4: The government today recalled two nominee directors  K. Ramalingam and O.P. Vaish  from the board of Maytas Infra, which was handed over to IL amp;FS on Monday.                             
	 New Delhi, Sept. 4: ONGC Videsh (OVL) and its partners Indian Oil and Oil India will invest about $5 billion in developing a massive gasfield in offshore Iran.                            
	 Mumbai, Sept. 4: TCS chief executive officer S. Ramadorai, who is retiring on October 5, will remain as non-executive vice-chairman of the company. He will also serve as an additional director. The appointment will be effective from October 6.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 4: Delhi High Court has directed the Drug Controller-General of India to process Ciplas licence application for the production and sale of the generic version of Bayer Corporations liver and kidney cancer drug Nexavar.                            
	 New Delhi, Sept. 4: The government may bear the account maintenance charges of the new pension scheme, an official with the pension regulator said.                                                                                                                           
